      <h1>⭐ Morning Briefing — Texas &amp; DFW AI Data Centers, Grid, Land Use</h1>
      <p class="briefing-subtitle">(Latest updates through July 24, 2026)</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>⚡ 1. ERCOT &amp; Grid Signals</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Batch Zero's Utility-Side Deadline Lands Today — The Nine-Month Interconnection Clock Starts Ticking for the First Wave</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Today, July 24, is the deadline for transmission and distribution service providers to submit the utility-side half of the Batch Zero technical package to ERCOT — the second of two required filings, following applicant-side submissions that closed July 10.</li>
        <li>The PUC approved ERCOT's Batch Zero large-load connection process on June 18, 2026, creating a structured on-ramp for the roughly 410 GW of large-load interconnection requests ERCOT is tracking statewide, about 87% of which are data centers.</li>
        <li>Once both halves of a Batch Zero filing are complete, ERCOT's nine-month interconnection study clock begins — meaning today's deadline effectively starts the timer for the first cohort of large loads to move through the new process.</li>
        <li>Standing context: the PUC's July 9 vote (5-0) to adopt "ride-through" rules — requiring data centers and other large loads to stay connected through grid disturbances rather than trip offline — continues to draw pushback, with operators estimating compliance costs of $500,000 to $1 million per megawatt and hinting at litigation.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Whatever gets filed today effectively sets the front of the queue for the state's new large-load interconnection process — worth watching in the coming weeks how many of the roughly 410 GW in pending requests actually clear this first procedural gate.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏗️ 2. Data Center Construction &amp; Corporate Activity</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">BlackRock Formally Launches Its $12.3B Bond Sale for Meta's El Paso Campus</p>
      <ul>
        <li>BlackRock began marketing a bond sale targeting more than $12.3 billion to help finance Meta's AI data-center campus in El Paso, with BlackRock's infrastructure arms taking roughly 80% ownership and Meta holding the remaining 20% — a structure designed to keep the debt off BlackRock's own balance sheet.</li>
        <li>The deal, arranged with major Wall Street banks and first reported last week by the Wall Street Journal and Bloomberg, is now moving to formal pricing; it ranks among the largest debt financings yet tied to a single U.S. data-center project.</li>
        <li>The El Paso campus draws on El Paso Electric's grid capacity and is expected to come online in 2028; Meta had already grown its committed investment there to roughly $10 billion as of March 2026.</li>
        <li>No new dated land purchase, interconnection filing, or air-permit application specific to the DFW metro surfaced today. JLL's 2026 market outlook still projects Texas overtaking Northern Virginia as the world's largest data-center market by 2030.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> The bond sale's growth from "more than $12 billion" last week to $12.3 billion in today's marketing suggests strong investor demand — worth watching whether final pricing confirms appetite for an off-balance-sheet structure this large, since it's likely to become the template for other Texas mega-campuses.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🌿 3. Environmental &amp; Air-Permit Activity (TCEQ)</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Ellis County's Midlothian Energy Permit Clears Its Comment Window as TCEQ Data Refreshes Today</p>
      <ul>
        <li>TCEQ's Title V pending-applications list, refreshed today (data updated 07/24/2026), shows Midlothian Energy LLC's draft operating-permit renewal (No. O1869) for its Ellis County gas-fired plant closed its 30-day public comment period on July 22, after the notice was authorized July 10.</li>
        <li>Other DFW-area filings still moving through the pipeline: MCC Manufacturing Inc. in Tarrant County, with a comment period running through August 12, and Acacia Natural Gas LLC in Parker County, whose comment period closed July 21.</li>
        <li>No new draft permit or public-notice posting appeared today specific to Collin, Johnson, Denton, Wise, or Hood counties.</li>
        <li>Backdrop: a January 2026 Houston Public Media report quoted environmental researchers warning that TCEQ lacks the staff and statutory tools to keep pace with data-center-linked gas-plant permitting statewide.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Midlothian Energy's filing is a renewal rather than a new build, but its Ellis County location sits inside the DFW ozone-nonattainment footprint — worth checking whether TCEQ issues a final decision or moves to a contested-case hearing next.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏛️ 4. Land-Use &amp; Zoning Developments</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">No New Filing Today — Fort Worth and Denton Both Still Parked on August Dates</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No new zoning filing or county-commissioner vote occurred today. Fort Worth's Zoning Commission voted 7-4 on July 8 to reject staff's proposed data-center standards (250-foot residential setbacks, generator siting limits, acoustic barriers for rooftop cooling equipment, and industrial-only zoning); five council members (Beck, Flores, Hall, Martinez, Nettles) are instead pushing a temporary moratorium, with City Council expected to take up both proposals August 11.</li>
        <li>City staff disclosed in a June presentation that data centers have generated more than $83 million in gross Fort Worth property-tax revenue over the past five years — a figure likely to shape the August 11 debate.</li>
        <li>No new rural land purchase, brownfield pivot, or industrial/warehouse filing masking data-center intent surfaced today for Parker, Hood, Wise, or the other outlying counties tracked in prior briefings.</li>
        <li>Statewide pressure continues to build: Gov. Abbott has named data-center regulation a priority for the 2027 legislative session and has asked PUC and ERCOT leadership to ensure data centers — not residential ratepayers — shoulder the cost of their own grid growth.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> With both Fort Worth and Denton parked on August council dates, the next real DFW zoning news is unlikely before the August 4–11 window — worth using the lull to track whether other North Texas counties file similar standards in the meantime.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🔌 5. Power-First Strategies &amp; On-Site Generation</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">GE Vernova's Gas-Turbine Backlog Hits 116 GW as Grid Wait Times Push Operators Off-Grid</p>
      <ul>
        <li>GE Vernova reported yesterday that its gas-turbine order backlog climbed to 116 GW, part of a total company order backlog of $176 billion — up from $129 billion in the same quarter last year — with CEO Scott Strazik saying the company is now taking turbine reservations for 2031 delivery.</li>
        <li>Coverage framed the backlog explicitly around AI infrastructure demand, with one report quoting the growing order book as evidence that "AI data centers cannot wait" for standard grid interconnection timelines — a dynamic directly fueling the shift toward behind-the-meter and on-site gas generation in Texas.</li>
        <li>Standing context: a July 2 study covered by KERA found Texas accounts for nearly half of the 74 proposed behind-the-meter gas plants tracked nationally, with potential combined emissions exceeding 287 million tons of greenhouse gases annually if all were built.</li>
        <li>Meta's El Paso campus continues to lean on more than 800 mobile mini-turbines for bridge power ahead of permanent on-site generation coming online.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> A multi-year turbine backlog now stretching to 2031 all but guarantees Texas operators will keep leaning on behind-the-meter and mobile generation as a bridge — worth watching whether that pushes more campuses toward the same modular-turbine approach Meta is using in El Paso.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>📍 6. Today's Watch List</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Actionable Signals for Friday, July 24</p>

